r:Citation.description: A survey was conducted among hospitality venues in Hungary and Slovakia to examine the use of music within the sector and to estimate the potential economic value generated by this usage. The survey was administered online via self-completion and targeted hospitality establishments such as restaurants, bars, cafés, and hotels. Questionnaires were completed by managers, owners, or other authorized representatives of the venues. A quota sampling approach was applied to ensure balanced representation across key business categories within NACE Section I. The sample was drawn from the verified ORBIS business database, and invitations were distributed via email through the Qualtrics platform. Only venues with valid email contact information were included in the outreach. In total, 17,759 venues in Hungary and 1,801 in Slovakia were contacted. The broader sampling frame comprised approximately 73,576 establishments across both countries—36,633 in Hungary and 36,943 in Slovakia. The final achieved sample included 43 respondents in Hungary and 23 in Slovakia. The questionnaire covered a wide range of topics relevant to hospitality operations. These included venue type, size, ownership, and operational characteristics; the use of background music—its sources, frequency, genres, equipment, and licensing practices; and the organization of live music events, including frequency, genres, equipment needs, revenue effects, customer impacts, and operational challenges. The survey also explored how venues perceive the economic role and value of music within their business activities.

r:Purpose.r:Content: T1.3. The survey data collection (lead: SSSA; contributors: SOZA, ARTISJUS, MUSICAUTOR, EUBA). [Start: M17, End: M32]. The first concerns what is potentially underrepresented in official statistics, calling for the development and distribution of surveys targeting both professionals and MSMEs, while also testing different sampling and distribution methodologies. The second is methodological: to assess the extent to which firm-level commercial databases can support survey implementation, particularly for MSMEs.
